content.problemStatement:
A tutorial for this problem is now available on our blog. Click here to read it. Knowing Johnny's mathematical talent, our teacher has prepared a new interesting problem for him, hoping he will enjoy solving it. The problem description is given below.

"There is a rectangular room of length l and width w (l and w are integers). The length and width of the room&nbsp; fulfill the relation l=Aw+B, where A and B are given integer constants. The room is divided into square cells of unit dimensions. You have observed that, after adding an integer C to the number of cells in the room, the number of cells becomes divisible by the prime number P. Find all the possible values of the width of the room."

&nbsp;

code.C:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int T;
    scanf("%d", &T);
    while (T--) {
        int A, B, C, P;
        scanf("%d %d %d %d", &A, &B, &C, &P);
        int count = 0;
        for (int w = 0; w < P; w++) {
            int l = (A * w + B) % P;
            int cells = (l * w) % P;
            if ((cells + C) % P == 0) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        printf("%d", count);
        for (int w = 0; w < P; w++) {
            int l = (A * w + B) % P;
            int cells = (l * w) % P;
            if ((cells + C) % P == 0) {
                printf(" %d", w);
            }
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}

